title: metal_gear_rex
body:
Metal Gear Rex is a mecha which appears in [[Metal Gear Solid]] and [spoiler]Metal Gear Solid 4 as a pilotable mecha[/spoiler].

Designed by [[Hal Emmerich]], it is armed with 30 Gatling cannon, anti-tank missiles, laser cannons and a large railgun [spoiler]which fires a projectile that is undetectable by any current ballistic missile detection systems and has an armor piercing warhead to penetrate bunkers[/spoiler]. Even though it is invulnerable to conventional attacks, its large radome is vulnerable to missile attacks.

In Metal Gear Solid, [spoiler][[Solid Snake]] is tricked by [[Liquid Snake]] to activate it[/spoiler], resulting in Solid Snake having to destroy it. After a battle, it was abandoned in the underground maintenance base. 

In Metal Gear Solid 4, [spoiler]Rex's railgun is removed prior to Solid Snake's (now known as [[Old Snake]]) arrival in Shadow Moses island. Solid Snake pilots it and engages [[Metal Gear RAY]], the Metal Gear designed to counter it, in battle outside the base. Due to the "Street Fighter" software control program which Hal Emmerich has secretly installed on Metal Gear Rex, Metal Gear won the battle and is abandoned after that[/spoiler].

title: last_man_battalion
body:
The [b]Last Man Battalion[/b], also known as the [b]LMB[/b], is one of four enemy factions from the videogame [[Tom Clancy's The Division]].

A Private Military Company composed of elite soldiers and operatives from the US Army's elite 75th Ranger Regiment and the CIA's Special Operations Group, they were hired by Wall Street business men to protect their assets in New York during the Green Poison outbreak. The LMB were at first allied with the Joint Task Force into bringing order in New York during the outbreak. However, the LMB's leader, Charles Bliss, began to view the JTF as weak in maintaining order as he and his men felt resentment for being abandoned during the outbreak. 

Eventually, Bliss and the LMB went rogue and aim to put New York City under their fascist, totalitarian rule where only the strong survive. Due to their military training and equipment, the LMB are the toughest enemies the Division face.

The LMB are usually seen with Winter Military uniforms and red armbands with a animal skull logo on it.

[b]Project Phoenix[/b] is an indie game being developed by [i]Creative Intelligence Arts[/i]. A squad-based real-time strategy video game combined with strong Japanese role-playing game design influence, the project is being described as [[Kickstarter]]'s first [[Japan]]-based video game project. The development team, self-described as "featuring AAA talent", includes [[Final Fantasy]] composer Uematsu Nobuo, and Arai Kiyoshi, an artist for [[Final Fantasy XII]] and [[Final Fantasy XIV|XIV]]. Violinist Yura Hiroaki will serve as the game's director and producer, while [[L.A. Noire]] QA analyst Vaughan Smith will be the game and battle designer.

The game's Kickstarter project successfully raised $1,014,600 (of $100,000 goal) on September 11, 2013; however, the project has since gone down as a disaster.

title: kumoko_(kumo_desu_ga_nani_ka?)
body:
[b]Alternate names:[/b] Nameless, No-Name, [spoiler]The Nightmare of the Labyrinth[/spoiler]

Kumoko (蜘蛛子) is a fan-made nickname for the main character of [[kumo desu ga nani ka?|Kumo desu ga, Nani ka?]], who had remained canonically nameless for a long time.

Kumoko's identity in the story is unknown at first (in the original web novel and light novels, even her gender is initially unknown), and any hints at her identity are therefore [[spoilers]] and [i]should be marked as such[/i].  She reincarnated after dying in a mysterious explosion in her high school literature class in the form of a [[spider]] within a monster-filled labyrinth and with gaps and inaccuracies in her memories of her original life, including her own name, and finds herself having to do everything she can just to survive.

[spoiler]She eventually evolves into an [[arachne]], at which point she is finally given a true name of her own by "D", becoming known as "[[Shiraori]]".[/spoiler]

Remember that "Kumoko" is the name of the [i]spider character[/i], and images that do not possess a spider form should not be tagged "Kumoko" to reduce needless spoilers.  [spoiler]Her hybrid arachne form unavoidably becomes a spoiler, and all images in her arachne form should be tagged as spoilers.[/spoiler]

She has an extensive "page in the Kumo Desu Ga Wiki":[https://kumodesu.fandom.com/wiki/Kumoko]

body:
[[Kamen Rider Agito]]'s final form and an evolution of his [[kamen rider agito (burning form)|Burning Form]]. It is accessible if he is exposed to the [[sunlight]].

Though it has lower punching power compared to the Burning Form (probably due to the Burning Form's armor being shed during the transformation into this form), the rest of Agito's parameters are higher in comparison. Thus, Shining Form is Agito's most potent form overall.

This form also allows the usage of the Shining Caliber, but Agito separates it into a pair of swords (called the Twin Mode) and uses them via [[dual wielding]].

His finishers while in this form are the:

* [i]Shining Clash[/i] - Delivers multiple slashes using the Shining Caliber in Twin Mode.
* [i]Shining Rider Kick[/i] - Stronger version of his Ground Form's [[Rider Kick]].

title: help:community_rules
body:
These Community Rules govern all social interactions between Danbooru users, including on the forum, in the comments, in private messages, and off-site in the Discord and on Github.

h4. General Rules

* Be friendly to other users.
* Don't insult, attack, abuse, threaten, or harass other users.
* Don't engage in hate speech, use racist or sexist slurs, or engage in other hateful conduct.
* Don't send spam.

h6. Account Rules

* Don't create multiple accounts to evade bans or to bypass account restrictions or limitations.
* Don't make usernames that insult, harass, or impersonate other users, or that use slurs, hate speech, or other derogatory language.

h6. Comment Rules

* Write comments in English. Other languages may be used if it's relevant to the post at hand, but in general, Danbooru is an English speaking website.
* Don't post unmarked spoilers. Use [code][spoiler][/spoiler][/code] tags to mark spoilers.
* Don't delete and repost comments to avoid downvotes.
* Don't abuse the voting system. Don't create multiple accounts to vote multiple times. Don't use bots or scripts to vote automatically. Don't mass downvote a user's comments to harass them.

h6. Forum Rules

* Don't use the forum for topics unrelated to Danbooru.
* Be civil to other users. Don't start flame wars because you disagree with someone.
* Be welcoming to new users. Don't be rude to new users because they posted in the wrong thread, asked a question in the wrong place, or asked a question that has already been answered.

h6. DMail Rules

* Don't use DMails to harass other users.
* Don't use DMails to trade or share content that is illegal or against Danbooru's rules.

h6. Post Rules

* Don't use flags to harass or target other uploaders.
* Don't flag posts if they don't break the [[help:upload_rules|upload rules]].
* Don't abuse the voting system. Don't create multiple accounts to vote multiple times. Don't use bots or scripts to vote automatically. Don't mass downvote a user's uploads to harass them.
* Don't engage in edit wars over tags. If there is disagreement over how a post should be tagged, bring it to the forum.

h6. User Feedback Rules

* Be civil when writing feedbacks. Don't insult or demean other users in feedbacks.
* Don't use the feedback system to attack or harass other users. Don't use feedbacks as a weapon to get users unfairly banned.

h6. Discord Rules

* Don't attack, insult, or talk negatively about other users, including Danbooru users not in the Discord.
* Don't post loli, shota, gore, bestiality, or any other content that is against Discord's terms of service.
* Take important discussions to the forum so that all users may participate.
* Obey the other rules listed in the #rules channel.

title: wacca
body:
WACCA is a 2019 arcade Rhythm Game developed by Marvelous Entertainment (of Senran Kagura fame) and the J-core record label HARDCORE TANO*C. It's best described as Lanota with a side of Chunithm and maimai, using a conical cabinet with a touch-sensitive interior around a circular screen. Its original soundtrack primarily features songs from the label's roster (including Aran, Massive New Krew, USAO, and t+pazolite, among others, who have been recent mainstays of other recent rhythm games), but much like its competitors, it still features a wide variety of anime, J-pop, [[Touhou]] Project, and [[Vocaloid]] licenses among others.

title: nixie_tube
body:
An electronic device used for displaying numerals or other information using glow discharge developed in the 1950's.  They're a glass tube filled with a low-pressure gas, such as neon, and contains a wire-mesh anode and multiple cathodes shaped like numerals or symbols.  Applying power to a specific cathode surrounds it with an orange glow discharge.

The technology was superseded in the 1970's by light-emitting diodes (LEDs) and vacuum fluorescent displays (VFDs).

h4. See also

title: tales_of_symphonia
body:
The fifth main entry in the [[tales of (series)|Tales Series]], as well as the first 3D entry. Released [[2003]] for the [[Gamecube|Nintendo GameCube]] in Japan and then in America the subsquent year, and then ported to the [[Playstation 2]] (in Japan only) with a small amount of extra content. Notable for being the series' first major hit in the west thanks to [[Nintendo]]'s involvement in the game's localization, as well as the dearth of RPGs on the GameCube at the time. In addition, a 12-episode OVA adaptation by [[ufotable]] was released sporadically from [[2007]] to [[2012]].

Tales of Symphonia follows 17-year-old Lloyd Irving's quest to keep his childhood friend and Chosen of Mana, Colette Brunel, safe on her journey to save the world of Sylvarant. This quest becomes an adventure through multiple worlds in a struggle to stop an endless cycle.

Tales of Symphonia takes place 4000 years before [[Tales of Phantasia]]. The game received a sequel, [[Tales of Symphonia Knight of Ratatosk]], in [[2008]].

title: antlion
body:
A large group of insects most well known for their fiercely predatory larva that feature large sickle-like jaws formed from their maxillae and mandibles.  They're also well known for their many members that will create pit traps out of loose material and wait at the bottom for prey to become trapped and slip down to where it can eat them.  Their adult forms aren't well recognized, partially due to their relatively short life compared to their larval forms.

While the origin of the name "antlion" isn't known, it is believed it stems from ants making up a large percent of their prey and for them being an aggressive hunter.  Their adult forms are sometimes referred to as "antlion lacewings," and in North American their larva are sometimes referred to as "doodlebugs" due to the squiggling trails they can leave in sand.

title: prowler_(titanfall)
body:
Prowlers are a species of carnivorous creatures from the [[Titanfall (series)|]] series. They are about the size of a large tiger and inhabit multiple planets in the Frontier, posing a formidable threat with their ability to easily maim and kill a human.

While they were present in the first game's concept art and referenced in dialogue, Prowlers did not actually appear in-game until [[Titanfall 2]]. They are also seen in [[Apex Legends]], as AI enemies that can be defeated for loot in [[Bloodhound (apex legends)|]]'s Trials on [[World's Edge]] and throughout the map on [[Storm Point (apex legends)|]]. 

TF2 and Apex's depictions of Prowlers can be distinguished by their color - in TF2 they are primarily black with yellow markings, while the Apex version is primarily red with blue stripes.

title: stickam
body:
A Japanese livestreaming site, founded in 2005 and shut down in 2013, where artists livestreamed their drawings.

Artists would sometimes post artwork on Pixiv to announce when they were streaming. These pictures were often deleted after a short amount of time.

'Stickam Delivery' means the art is a delivery of the completed artwork from the live stream.
